<br>
The trick is getting those smithed parts (studs/boning) for the progressive leather armor. Shopping for ore, making bits to make studs or boning: it runs into a little money. BUT - you can get all the ore for studs and boning you need without buying a single brick of ore.<br>
<br>
What you need: A sharpening stone; all the rusty weapons you can get; plenty of water flasks.<br>
<br>
Sharpening stones can be purchased off of some smithing vendors; I got mine in Freeport. You only need one as it's never used up.<br>
<br>
Sharpen those rusty weapons. You get tarnished weapons as a result and can skill up to the mid-20s this way. You lose nothing on either success or failure; the stone is always returned and failure returns the rusty weapon, so just try again.<br>
<br>
Now that you have the tarnished weapons, throw it in the oven with a water flask. Depending on the weapon, this produces different sized pieces/bricks of ore. Larger pieces/bricks of ore can then be broken into smaller components by using a smithing chisel. Once you have two small pieces of ore, combine with a water flask to get metal bits, then combine the metal bits with a file mold and water flask to get a file. You only need one file, it's never used up.<br>
<br>
For studs, you need 3 metal bits, a file, and a water flask. For boning, it's a small brick of ore, file, and water flask.<br>
<br>
Studded and reinforced leather armor for the cost of a sharpening stone and a file mold. That should make it a little easier to bridge some of the gaps between raw silk/backpacks/quivers, as the trivial for studded leather is 56 and reinforced leather is 102. One more tip, make the masks, they only need one stud/boning per piece. Unless you just want to make a whole set of armor for some reason. Plus the armor should sell back to vendors for well over the cost of the pattern (which is all you're spending to make it), so it makes 0-100 tailoring more profitable as well.<br>
